Simplify the Stage 7 (CAP & BU Reconciliation) status model from three statuses (Mapped / Needs BU / Archived) with two sub-labels (New CAP / Retired BU) to a clean two-status model. The new model is significantly simpler and aligned with how the reconciliation logic actually works.
Why this change: the previous design overcomplicated things. CAPs that were in the previous mapping but no longer appear in the current Stage 3 output are not relevant to the reviewer — those CAPs are audited in the source system (Archer) and don't need to be carried forward in the pipeline. The distinction between "new CAP" and "retired BU" wasn't earning its place either, because the reviewer's action is the same for both: pick a BU. Collapsing to two statuses makes the workflow faster and the UI more scannable.
Do not modify the engine's underlying status calculation logic — only the user-facing labels, the page copy, the filter chips, the column structure, and the review table presentation are being updated. The reconciliation algorithm itself follows this logic: iterate over every CAP in the current Stage 3 output, look up the CAP in the previously uploaded CAP→BU mapping. If the CAP is not in the previous mapping, status is Unassigned. If the CAP is in the previous mapping AND its BU is in the current Stage 6 BU list, status is OK. If the CAP is in the previous mapping but its BU is no longer in the current Stage 6 BU list, status is Unassigned.

SECTION 1: NEW TWO-STATUS MODEL
Replace all references to the previous status vocabulary with the new model:
Status: OK
When: CAP exists in previous mapping AND its BU is in the current Stage 6 list
What the reviewer does: Nothing — assignment carries forward
Status: Unassigned
When: CAP is not in the previous mapping, OR its previous BU is no longer in the current Stage 6 list
What the reviewer does: Pick a current BU from the dropdown
No sub-labels. No third status. The distinction between "new CAP" and "retired BU" is no longer surfaced — both end up as "Unassigned" because the reviewer's action is the same in both cases.
CAPs that are in the previous mapping but no longer appear in the current Stage 3 output are excluded from the reconciliation entirely. They do not appear in the review table.

